[src:guy-zinn/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:guy-zinn/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] The **Baltimore Terrapins** were a team in the short-lived Federal League of professional baseball from 1914 to 1915.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] Their brief existence led to litigation that led to an important legal precedent in baseball.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] The team played its home games at Terrapin Park.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] Most of the professional baseball teams in Baltimore have been called the Orioles, in reference to the Baltimore oriole bird.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] There was already a minor league Baltimore Orioles, and the new Federal League club built their ballpark directly across the street from the Orioles park.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] The new club chose to call itself the Baltimore Terrapins, after the diamondback terrapin, the state reptile of Maryland.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] That nickname would later become primarily associated with the University of Maryland, College Park sports teams called the Maryland Terrapins.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore gathered for spring training in Southern Pines, North Carolina at the Southern Pines Golf Club, previously used by the Philadelphia Phillies in 1909 and 1910.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] Terrapins manager Otto Knabe had played for these Phillies teams and trained in Southern Pines.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] While the 1914 team posted a respectable 84–70 record and finished only 4½ games out of first place under player-manager Otto Knabe, the team was less than successful at the box office, even though four of the eight teams in the league (Chicago, Brooklyn, Pittsburgh, and St.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) were competing with one and even two (Chicago and St.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) other major league teams in the same cities.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] In an attempt to turn this situation around and attract a marquee player to help them at the box office, the 1915 team recruited Chief Bender of the American League champion Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] The Athletics had sold off several future Hall-of-Famers like Eddie Plank, Eddie Collins and Frank "Home Run" Baker after being swept by the surprising Boston Braves in the 1914 World Series.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] Bender had come off an impressive 17–3 season where he compiled seven shutouts and a 2.26 ERA in 1914.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] However, his 1915 season at Baltimore was a low point of his Hall of Fame career when he slumped to a 4–16 record, no shutouts, and a 3.99 ERA.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore's collapse to a 47–107 record, 40 games out of first, was overshadowed only by the collapse of Bender's former team who went from a 99–53 league championship season to a dismal 43–109 record, 58½ games out of first in 1915.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] Bender and the Baltimore Terrapins never made a full recovery from 1915.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] The incident did show the Federal League could compete seriously with the National League and American League on a professional baseball level and led to the buy-out truce which ended the Federal League for good.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] However, the Baltimore team's owners were not offered a part in this buyout.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] When the Federal League started, the Terrapins severely cut into the minor league Baltimore Orioles' attendance, causing financial problems for the owner.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] As a result, several players, including the young left-handed pitcher Babe Ruth, were offered for sale to major league teams.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] Ruth's contract was purchased by the Boston Red Sox, after being turned down by Connie Mack and the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] In 1914, Ruth began his career with the Red Sox of the rival American League.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] After the demise of the Federal League and the Terrapins, Baltimore would not see major league baseball again until 1954, when the former St.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] Louis Browns moved into town and became the present-day Baltimore Orioles.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] As the Terrapins' owners were not offered any part of the buyout offer made to most Federal League teams by the American and National Leagues, they decided to sue, alleging that the buyout was in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] Supreme Court deciding that the scheduling and playing of "base ball games" did not constitute "interstate commerce" in any sense envisioned by the Framers of the United States Constitution; therefore, the Sherman Act and other federal laws and regulations did not apply to baseball.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] National League*, was not ultimately decided until 1922.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] The minor league Orioles moved into Terrapin Park, a wooden ballpark.
[src:guy-zinn/baltimore-terrapins] This move began a chain of events which would eventually lead to the return of major league baseball to Baltimore.
[src:guy-zinn/guy-zinn] Zinn played his first game on September 11, 1911, for the New York Highlanders of the American League.
[src:guy-zinn/guy-zinn] On April 20, 1912, he scored the first-ever run at Fenway Park.
[src:guy-zinn/guy-zinn] In 1912, he played 106 games for the Highlanders with 105 hits and 6 home runs (fourth in the American League) with 55 runs batted in.
[src:guy-zinn/guy-zinn] The next season, in 1913, he played for the Boston Braves of the National League, hitting .297 in 36 games.
[src:guy-zinn/guy-zinn] He played his final two seasons for the Baltimore Terrapins of the Federal League, garnering 147 hits and 8 home runs over that period.
[src:guy-zinn/guy-zinn] He played his last game on September 16, 1915, with Baltimore.
[src:guy-zinn/guy-zinn] His career batting average was .269, with 297 hits.
